references: We start our exploration by examining the convergence of FL4ASRFL4ASR\mathrm{FL4ASR} training. For this, we use Stochastic Gradient Descent (SGDSGD\mathrm{SGD}) as the local optimizer and tune over the two central optimizers: (i) AdamAdam\mathrm{Adam} [28] as suggested in [13] and (ii) SGDSGD\mathrm{SGD} as suggested in [21]. In order to obtain a converging model it is important to use learning rate scheduler and data augmentation [26, 27] as can be seen in Table 3 (rows 3-3, 3-3, 3-3). The main takeaways are as follows:

These observations correspond to a reduction in heterogeneity among client updates at various stages of training: warmup and decay scheduler for LR ensure smaller LR at the start and end of training respectively and data augmentation prevents model overfitting to local data, thus reducing heterogeneity among of model updates from client in FL [13, 29]. It is worth noting that among pre-layer norm and post-layer norm, only the former consistently converges on all training data sizes using FL. Also, during our initial experiments summarized in Table 3, we observe that SGDSGD\mathrm{SGD} outperforms AdamAdam\mathrm{Adam} when using default parameters, i.e., ε=1​e−8𝜀1e8\varepsilon=1\mathrm{e}-8. In fact, AdamAdam\mathrm{Adam} fails to converge with default parameters as can be seen in Table 3.

While tuning epsilon ε𝜀\varepsilon in AdamAdam\mathrm{Adam} in centralized training affects both the numerical stability and the magnitude of model updates [30] during optimization, we observe diverging training for all values of ε∈{0.1,0.01,1​e−5,1​e−8}𝜀0.10.011e51e8\varepsilon\in\{0.1,0.01,1\mathrm{e}-5,1\mathrm{e}-8\} (see rows 3, 3, 3 in Table 3) when using FL.

references: One of the main challenges in FL is handling heterogeneous data. In the case of ASR, the heterogeneity can be w.r.t both acoustic features of the speaker (input space), and token frequency in the transcripts (output space). Also, the depth of the model only aggravates this problem. These observations correspond to a reduction in heterogeneity among client updates at various stages of training: warmup and decay scheduler for LR ensure smaller LR at the start and end of training respectively and data augmentation prevents model overfitting to local data, thus reducing heterogeneity among of model updates from client in FL [13, 29]. One of the main challenges in FL is handling heterogeneous data. In the case of ASR, the heterogeneity can be w.r.t both acoustic features of the speaker (input space), and token frequency in the transcripts (output space). Also, the depth of the model only aggravates this problem.
